\b \cf0 Functional Description\
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5032\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf0 \
A new user of the system will be required to create a user account.\
\
Once a user account has been created a user may begin creating assets. Assets include questions, choice lists (for graded answers), and surveys. Surveys will comprise one or more 
\i survey items
\i0 . Each survey item will contain the text of a question, a choice list (of graded answers) and a text input area for peers to provide an explanation of their choice of grade.\
\
Once a user has designed a survey he/she may propose the start of a peer review process by providing a list of one or more peers (selected from users of the system), a list of zero or more overseers (who will be authorized to view the responses of peers), and various options, such as a text description of the proposed process, an option to allow peers to evaluate themselves, and an option to disable anonymity of responses.\
\
Once a process has been proposed, each nominated peer will receive notification that they are expected to participate in a peer review process, along with a actionable link to affirm their acceptance of this expectation.\
\
When all peers have accepted, each peer will be provided access to a copy of the survey for each other peer in the process. Peers will enter and submit their responses to the questions (survey items) on the survey for each of their co-peers. When all responses have been submitted the system will collate the responses of each peer for each question and provide a means for each peer to review this collated set of responses.\
\
Users will have the ability to create new versions of their assets, effectively editing their assets, without impacting the integrity of existing peer review processes.\
\
Integration with IBM Watson is specified. Mood analysis data and possibly other data are to be displayed in appropriate places (e.g. where text input of any kind is done) to help users to be thoughtful in formulating both questions and responses.\
\

\b Use Cases\uc0\u8232 
\b0 \
Use cases could include any group or team involved in any corporate, academic, open source, or social endeavor. In any project or situation where a peer review process is appropriate, the system is intended provide a clean, functional alternative to manual administration of such a process.\
\

\b User Community
\b0 \uc0\u8232 \
Because the system provides options for creating peer review processes with custom rules on anonymity and oversight, a wide variety of user communities could make use of the system. A design goal of the system is to provide a general system that is easily configured to requirements or needs of any user community.\
\

\b Administration Functions\uc0\u8232 
\b0 \
The prototype system will be administered via a third-party interface to MySQL. The system should require very little administration. However, it may be proper for an expanded prototype to provide for administrative users and functionality to manage database maintenance issues that may emerge from the design (such as manual garbage collection, backup, and restore).\uc0\u8232 \

\b Error Handling\

\b0 \uc0\u8232 Error handling issues may exist on a number of application levels (e.g. database, connectivity, program logic, hacking detection/prevention, etc.)\
\
The original specification does not provide robust requirements for error handing. The prototype system will be designed to identify, detect and handle as many error situations as is practical. Care will be taken so the system does not depend on the disregard of any known error event or state. \
\

